<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,1239,1372]" pageId="20" pageNumber="363">
When the animal was active, it held its tegmina more or less vertically (Fig, 
<number box="[1050,1078,1276,1300]" pageId="20" pageNumber="363" value="13.0">13</number>
A). However, during the day, at rest the animal sat motionless with the tegmina flat above the body (
<figureCitation box="[942,1024,1311,1336]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[205,1336,193,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[205,1337,193,1858]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Habitus. A— Oxyaspis congensis, active, B— Oxyaspis congensis, nearly at rest, C— Zabalius apicalis inversus, D— Pantecphylus (P.) helleri, E— Batodromeus subulo, F— Lichenochrus congicus, G— Leproscirtus granulosus ♂, H— Leproscirtus granulosus ♀, I— Karniella crassicerca, J— Plastocorypha ituriana." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/250521/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[996,1024,1311,1335]" pageId="20" pageNumber="363" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
